snippet.textDisplay:
Maybe Brendan is, unknown even to himself, one of the "forgotten Doctors" ala Ruth. Maybe the "true" first incarnation. He is even ginger as a child, (though I realize that was a Moffet bit more than anything else.) Grew up/slept in barns as a youngster (Hell Bent) not unlike the one he's seen working in his growing up montage from the episode. Played with a plane, flying about and exploring. Drawn to a protection-oriented profession. Carrying a time-piece around prominently after his retirement party from the Guard. Memory wiped by ageless (timeless) looking people close to him.
Didn't regenerate after the fall off the cliff, true. He came back to life more like Harkness does. But maybe a bullet and a fall like that wouldn't kill a Time Lord in their prime, I have no idea. Something like this would certainly "change everything" as has been promised by the Master all year.

What happens if the Darleks show up as well. I mean it's possible for them to want to destroy the cybermen, because they want to be the superior race in the universe.

How is the Doctor going to correct the ultication that is about to be done. Maybe that's why there is now two doctors who don't know each others existence, existing at the same time.

snippet.textDisplay:
Feelings after the episode... I'm way beyond confused, as Graham would say, and not in the best way this time. The pacing felt either too slow or too fast throughout the episode imo, but there's an interesting parallel to Dalek Invasion of Earth with Cybermen, making the Cybermen stand out once again (I like that). The two stories intertwined in a very strange way, and the conclusion to Brendan's story felt a bit rushed although I get what they were aiming at, and there may be a few things left unexplained or rushed about the origins and motives of the Lone Cyberman (if I got that right), but in terms of the episode itself, I felt most of the weight (if not all) was left to the second part which is an odd decision. This might be the first episode I was slightly disappointed at this season. I kept finding more cons than pros and the pieces went everywhere and nowhere at the same time. Apart from the Master coming at the end in style and the revelation of Gallifrey being on the other side of the Boundary as well as a splitted team in danger, I don't think the story provided enough juice for the final episode and it's going somewhere I'm not entirely sure yet, leaving me more confused, but since it's a two-parter, I'm expecting most of the surprises to be left for the end. It's too soon to say anything, but...


Ok, things I loved to see - The drone and new Cybermen designs were brilliant, I loved how ruthless and dominating they were for once (even though it was a small population, but most of it was deleted or converted), the Master returning in style (how did he know the right moment to pop in? Very convenient timing...). Also, why does the Boundary have that name? I found that intriguing and this means there's a direct open passage to Gallifrey. I wonder which implications this has.
